    <h1>Measures of Central Tendency</h1>

    <div class="section">
        <p>
            Measures of central tendency are statistical tools used to identify the central or representative value
            of a dataset. They provide a concise summary of data and are widely used in engineering, data analysis,
            machine learning, and decision-making.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>1. Mean</h2>

        <h3>Mean for Discrete Data</h3>
        <p>
            The arithmetic mean of a discrete data set is calculated by dividing the sum of all observations
            by the total number of observations.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
        <p>x̄ = (Σx) / n</p>

        <p><strong>Where:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>x = observation</li>
            <li>n = number of observations</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
        <p>Data: 10, 20, 30, 40, 50</p>
        <p>Mean = (10 + 20 + 30 + 40 + 50) / 5 = <strong>30</strong></p>

        <h3>Mean for Continuous (Grouped) Data</h3>
        <p>
            For grouped data, the mean is calculated using class midpoints and frequencies.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
        <p>x̄ = (Σf·x) / Σf</p>

        <p><strong>Where:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>f = frequency</li>
            <li>x = class midpoint</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Engineering Application:</strong></p>
        <p>
            Mean is used in signal processing, performance evaluation, and quality control.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>2. Median</h2>

        <h3>Median for Discrete Data</h3>
        <p>
            The median is the middle value when data is arranged in ascending or descending order.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Arrange data in order</li>
            <li>If n is odd → Median = middle value</li>
            <li>If n is even → Median = average of two middle values</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
        <p>Data: 15, 20, 25, 30, 35</p>
        <p>Median = <strong>25</strong></p>

        <h3>Median for Continuous (Grouped) Data</h3>
        <p>
            The median is calculated using the median class and cumulative frequency.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
        <p>
            Median = l + [ ((N/2) − cf) / f ] × h
        </p>

        <p><strong>Where:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>l = lower boundary of median class</li>
            <li>N = total frequency</li>
            <li>cf = cumulative frequency before median class</li>
            <li>f = frequency of median class</li>
            <li>h = class width</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Median is preferred for skewed data such as income, network latency, or response time analysis.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>3. Mode</h2>

        <h3>Mode for Discrete Data</h3>
        <p>
            Mode is the value that occurs most frequently in a dataset.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
        <p>Data: 2, 4, 4, 6, 8</p>
        <p>Mode = <strong>4</strong></p>

        <h3>Mode for Continuous (Grouped) Data</h3>
        <p>
            Mode is calculated using the modal class (class with the highest frequency).
        </p>

        <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
        <p>
            Mode = l + [ (f₁ − f₀) / (2f₁ − f₀ − f₂) ] × h
        </p>

        <p><strong>Where:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>l = lower boundary of modal class</li>
            <li>f₁ = frequency of modal class</li>
            <li>f₀ = frequency of preceding class</li>
            <li>f₂ = frequency of succeeding class</li>
            <li>h = class width</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Mode is especially useful for categorical data and market demand analysis.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Comparison of Mean, Median, and Mode</h2>

        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>Aspect</th>
                <th>Mean</th>
                <th>Median</th>
                <th>Mode</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Definition</td>
                <td>Arithmetic average of all values</td>
                <td>Middle value of ordered data</td>
                <td>Most frequently occurring value</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Formula</td>
                <td>Σx / n</td>
                <td>Depends on position (N/2)</td>
                <td>Frequency-based</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Sensitivity to Outliers</td>
                <td>Highly sensitive</td>
                <td>Not sensitive</td>
                <td>Not affected</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Suitable for Skewed Data</td>
                <td>No</td>
                <td>Yes</td>
                <td>Yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Applicable to Categorical Data</td>
                <td>No</td>
                <td>No</td>
                <td>Yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Engineering Applications</td>
                <td>Performance analysis, optimization</td>
                <td>Network latency, income analysis</td>
                <td>Demand analysis, classification</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>


</body>
