    <h1>Measures of Dispersion</h1>

    <div class="section">
        <p>
            Measures of dispersion describe the extent to which data values are spread or scattered around
            a central value. While measures of central tendency indicate the average behavior, dispersion
            measures help assess variability, consistency, and reliability of data.
        </p>
        <p>
            In engineering, dispersion is crucial for performance analysis, quality control, reliability
            testing, and data-driven modeling.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>1. Range</h2>
        <p>
            Range is the simplest measure of dispersion and represents the difference between the maximum
            and minimum values of a dataset.
        </p>

        <div class="formula">
            Range = Maximum value − Minimum value
        </div>

        <p><strong>Example (Discrete Data):</strong></p>
        <p>Data: 10, 20, 35, 50, 60</p>
        <p>Range = 60 − 10 = <strong>50</strong></p>

        <p>
            Range provides a quick estimate of spread but is highly sensitive to extreme values.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>2. Variance</h2>

        <h3>Variance for Discrete Data</h3>
        <p>
            Variance measures the average squared deviation of each observation from the mean.
        </p>

        <div class="formula">
            σ² = Σ(x − x̄)² / n
        </div>

        <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
        <p>Data: 2, 4, 6</p>
        <p>Mean = 4</p>
        <p>
            Variance = [(2−4)² + (4−4)² + (6−4)²] / 3 = <strong>8 / 3</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>Variance for Continuous (Grouped) Data</h3>
        <p>
            For grouped data, variance is calculated using class midpoints and frequencies.
        </p>

        <div class="formula">
            σ² = Σf(x − x̄)² / Σf
        </div>

        <p>
            Variance is widely used in signal processing, control systems, and data modeling.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>3. Standard Deviation</h2>
        <p>
            Standard deviation is the square root of variance and expresses dispersion in the same units
            as the original data, making it easier to interpret.
        </p>

        <div class="formula">
            σ = √σ²
        </div>

        <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
        <p>If variance = 9</p>
        <p>Standard deviation = √9 = <strong>3</strong></p>

        <p>
            A smaller standard deviation indicates that data values are closer to the mean,
            while a larger value indicates greater variability.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>4. Coefficient of Variation (CV)</h2>
        <p>
            The coefficient of variation is a relative measure of dispersion that compares
            the standard deviation with the mean.
        </p>

        <div class="formula">
            CV = (σ / x̄) × 100
        </div>

        <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
        <p>Mean = 50, Standard Deviation = 5</p>
        <p>CV = (5 / 50) × 100 = <strong>10%</strong></p>

        <p>
            CV is useful for comparing variability between datasets with different units or means,
            such as comparing machine efficiency or system performance.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Importance of Measures of Dispersion</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Help assess consistency and reliability of data</li>
            <li>Support risk analysis and quality assurance</li>
            <li>Essential in AI, ML, and data science models</li>
            <li>Used in network traffic analysis and performance tuning</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Measures of dispersion complement measures of central tendency and together provide
            a complete statistical description of data.
        </p>
    </div>


</body>
</html>

