    <h1>Skewness and Data Distribution</h1>

    <div class="section">
        <p>
            Skewness describes the degree of asymmetry in a data distribution around its mean.
            While measures of central tendency and dispersion summarize data numerically,
            skewness explains the <em>shape</em> of the distribution.
        </p>
        <p>
            Understanding skewness is essential in engineering, data science, machine learning,
            economics, and network performance analysis.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Data Distribution</h2>
        <p>
            A data distribution shows how values are spread across different ranges.
            It is commonly visualized using histograms or frequency curves.
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>Symmetric distribution:</strong> Mean = Median = Mode</li>
            <li><strong>Positively skewed distribution:</strong> Mean &gt; Median &gt; Mode</li>
            <li><strong>Negatively skewed distribution:</strong> Mean &lt; Median &lt; Mode</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            The shape of the distribution affects the choice of statistical methods
            and interpretation of results.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Skewness</h2>
        <p>
            Skewness measures the lack of symmetry in a frequency distribution.
            A perfectly symmetric distribution has zero skewness.
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>Zero Skewness:</strong> Symmetric distribution</li>
            <li><strong>Positive Skewness:</strong> Tail extends to the right</li>
            <li><strong>Negative Skewness:</strong> Tail extends to the left</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Graphical Representation of Skewness</h2>
        <p>
            Graphs help visualize the shape of a data distribution and clearly indicate
            whether the data is symmetric, positively skewed, or negatively skewed.
        </p>

        <div class="highlight">
            <p><strong>Symmetric Distribution (Sk = 0)</strong></p>
            <p>Mean = Median = Mode</p>
        </div>

        <div class="highlight">
            <p><strong>Positively Skewed Distribution (Right Skew)</strong></p>
            <p>Mode &lt; Median &lt; Mean</p>
        </div>

        <div class="highlight">
            <p><strong>Negatively Skewed Distribution (Left Skew)</strong></p>
            <p>Mean &lt; Median &lt; Mode</p>
        </div>

        <p><strong>From the graphs:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Symmetric distribution → Mean = Median = Mode</li>
            <li>Positive skewness → Mean &gt; Median &gt; Mode</li>
            <li>Negative skewness → Mean &lt; Median &lt; Mode</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Karl Pearson’s Coefficient of Skewness</h2>

        <p><strong>Formula (when mode is known):</strong></p>
        <div class="formula">
            Sk = (Mean − Mode) / Standard Deviation
        </div>

        <p><strong>Formula (when mode is not known):</strong></p>
        <div class="formula">
            Sk = 3(Mean − Median) / Standard Deviation
        </div>

        <p><strong>Solved Example (Positive Skewness):</strong></p>
        <p>Mean = 60, Median = 55, Standard Deviation = 10</p>
        <p>
            Sk = 3(60 − 55) / 10 = 15 / 10 = <strong>1.5</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            Since skewness is positive, the distribution is right-skewed.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Bowley’s Coefficient of Skewness</h2>
        <p>
            Bowley’s method is used when quartiles are available and is suitable
            for open-ended distributions.
        </p>

        <div class="formula">
            Sk = (Q₃ + Q₁ − 2Q₂) / (Q₃ − Q₁)
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Q₁ = First quartile</li>
            <li>Q₂ = Median</li>
            <li>Q₃ = Third quartile</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Solved Example (Negative Skewness):</strong></p>
        <p>Q₁ = 30, Q₂ = 40, Q₃ = 45</p>
        <p>
            Sk = (45 + 30 − 2×40) / (45 − 30) = (75 − 80) / 15 = <strong>-0.33</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
            Negative skewness indicates a left-skewed distribution.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Symmetric Distribution Example</h2>
        <p>Mean = Median = Mode = 50</p>
        <p>
            Since all three measures are equal, skewness is zero and the data
            is perfectly symmetric.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Engineering and Data Science Applications</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Performance analysis and response time evaluation</li>
            <li>Income and demand analysis</li>
            <li>Feature distribution analysis in Machine Learning</li>
            <li>Network traffic and latency modeling</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Skewness helps engineers and analysts choose suitable statistical models
            and make reliable predictions.
        </p>
    </div>


</body>
</html>

